io.spine.server.entity.storage

Class EntityColumn

  • java.lang.Object
    • io.spine.server.entity.storage.EntityColumn
  • All Implemented Interfaces:
    java.io.Serializable

    public class EntityColumn
extends java.lang.Object
implements java.io.Serializable
    The representation of a field of an Entity which is stored in the storage in the way efficient for querying.

    A entity column is a value retrieved from an Entity getter, which is marked as Column.

    Columns are inherited (both from classes and from interfaces). A getter for a column should be annotated only once, i.e. in the place of its declaration.

    Column names

    A column has different names for storing and for querying.

    A name for working with queries is determined by a name of column getter, e.g. value for getValue(). A client should specify this value to a column filters.

    A name, which is used for keeping a column in a Storage is determined by the column annotation property.

    Examples

    These methods represent the columns: 

          

         --UserGroupAggregate.java--

         \@Column
         public int getUserCount() {
             return getState().getUserCount();
         }

         --PaymentProcessManager.java--

         \@Nullable
         \@Column
         public Date getPaymentSystemName() {
             if (getState().hasExpirationDate()) {
                 return new Date();
             } else {
                 return null;
             }
         }

    And these methods are not considered to represent columns: 

          
         --UserAggregate.java--

         // only methods annotated with @Column may be considered Columns
         public Department getDepartment() { ... }

         // non-public methods may not represent Columns
         \@Column
         private double getHourRate() { ... }

         // only methods starting with "get" or "is" may be considered Columns
         \@Column
         public boolean hasChildren() { ... }

         // getter methods must not accept arguments
         \@Column
         public User getStateOf(UserAggregate other) { ... }

         // only instance methods are considered Columns
         \@Column
         public static Integer isNew(UserAggregate aggregate) { ... }

    Type policy

    An entity column can turn into any type. If use a ready implementation of the Spine Storages, the most commonly used types should be already supported. However, you may override the behavior for any type whenever you wish. For more info, see ColumnTypeRegistry.

    To handle specific types of the columns, which are not supported by default, implement the ColumnType interface, register it in a ColumnTypeRegistry and pass the instance of the registry into the StorageFactory on creation.

    Note that the type of an column must either be primitive or implement Serializable.

    Nullability

    A column may turn into null value if the getter which declares it is annotated as javax.annotation.Nullable. Otherwise, the entity column is considered non-null.

    If a non-null getter method returns null when trying to get the value of a column, a RuntimeException is thrown. See EntityColumn.isNullable().

    The example below shows a faulty column, which will throw RuntimeException when trying to get its value. 

         
         --EmployeeProjection.java--

         // method should be annotated as @Nullable to return a null value
         \@Column
         public Message getAddress() {
             return null;
         }

    This class is effectively final since it has a single private constructor. Though the modifier "final" is absent to make it possible to create mocks for testing.

    See Also:
    ColumnType, Serialized Form

      • getPersistedType

        public java.lang.Class getPersistedType()
        Returns the type under which the column values are persisted in the data storage.

        For the non-Enumerated entity columns this type will be equal to the one retrieved via the EntityColumn.getType().

        For the Enumerated columns, see EnumConverter implementations.

        Returns:
        the persistence type of the column values

      • toPersistedValue

        public @Nullable java.io.Serializable toPersistedValue(@Nullable java.lang.Object columnValue)
        Converts the column value into the value for persistence in the data storage.

        This method can be used to transform the value obtained through the EntityColumn getter into the corresponding value used for persistence in the data storage.

        The value type should be the same as the one obtained through the EntityColumn.getType(). The output value type will be the same as EntityColumn.getPersistedType().

        As the column value may be nullable, and all null values are persisted in the data storage as null, i.e. without any conversion, for the null input argument this method will always return null.

        The method is accessible outside of the EntityColumn class to enable the proper ColumnFilter conversion for the Enumerated column values.

        Parameters:
        columnValue - the column value to convert
        Returns:
        the column value converted to the form used for persistence in the data storage
        Throws:
        java.lang.IllegalArgumentException - if the value type is not equal to the entity column type
